<handout>
  <title>Exam 1 - Spring 2026</title>

<section>
<title>Topics</title>

    <p>1.1-1.7
    </p>

    <p>
      Be sure to try each question before looking at the solutions.
    </p>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-sp26exam1">
    <title>Questions</title>

 <exercise xml:id="exam1-s26-q4">
  <statement>
    <p>
      The value <m>V</m> (in dollars) of a painting <m>t</m> years after it is purchased is modeled by
      <me>V(t)=\frac{100t^2+50}{t}+400, \qquad 1\le t\le 5.</me>
    </p>
    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <p>
          Find the average rate of change in the value of the painting between the first
          (<m>t=1</m>) and fifth (<m>t=5</m>) years. Give proper units.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          In one sentence, explain the meaning of the value <m>V'(4)</m> in this context.
          Be sure to include proper units in your response.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
    <p>
      <m>V(1)=550</m> and <m>V(5)=910</m>, so the average rate of change is
      <me>AV_{[1,5]} = \frac{910-550}{5-1}=90</me>
      dollars per year.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>V'(4)</m> represents the instantaneous rate at which the value of the painting
      is changing, measured in dollars per year, four years after purchase.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
  </answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-s26-q5">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Calculate each one-sided limit below or state that it does not exist. Justify your answer.
    </p>
    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 0^-}\frac{-x^2+2x}{x(x-3)}</m>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 2^-}\frac{3x-6}{|4-x^2|}</m>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 2^+}\frac{3x-6}{|4-x^2|}</m>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <ol marker="a.">
        <li>
          <p>
       <m>
          \displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow 0^-}\frac{x^{2}+2x}{x(x-3)}= \lim_{x \rightarrow 0^-}\frac{x(x+2)}{x(x-3)}= \lim_{x \rightarrow 0^-}\frac{x+2}{x-3}= -\frac{2}{3}
      </m>
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>
          \displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow 2^-}\frac{3x-6}{|4-x^{2}|}= \lim_{x \rightarrow 2^-}\frac{3(x-2)}{4-x^{2}}= \lim_{x \rightarrow 2^-}\frac{3(x-2)}{(2-x)(2+x)}= \lim_{x \rightarrow 2^-}\frac{-3}{2+x}= -\frac{3}{4}
      </m>
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>
          \displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow 2^+}\frac{3x-6}{|4-x^{2}|}= \lim_{x \rightarrow 2^+}\frac{3(x-2)}{-(4-x^{2})}= \lim_{x \rightarrow 2^+}\frac{3}{x+2}= \frac{3}{4}
      </m>
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
  </answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-s26-q6">
  <statement>
    <p>
      During a chemical reaction, the temperature is modeled by <m>T(t)</m>,
      measured in degrees Celsius, where time <m>t</m> is measured in minutes.
      At <m>t=4</m> minutes, the derivative is <m>T'(4)=0.8</m>.
      Which statement correctly interprets this?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>At 4 minutes, the temperature is increasing at a rate of <m>0.8^\circ\text{C}</m> per minute.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>The temperature increases by <m>4^\circ</m> every 0.8 minutes.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. This is a rate, but not an instantaneous rate.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>The temperature is <m>0.8^\circ\text{C}</m> at 4 minutes.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. A derivative involves the rate of change.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
          <p>Between 3 and 4 minutes, the temperature increased by exactly <m>0.8^\circ\text{C}</m>.</p>
      </statement>
       <feedback>
        <p>No. The rate of change should be instant and not over a time interval of 1 minute.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
          <p>The temperature has increased by a total of <m>0.8^\circ\text{C}</m> since the reaction began.</p>
      </statement>
       <feedback>
        <p>No. This is not an instantaneous rate.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise> 

<exercise xml:id="exam1-s26-q7">
  <statement>
    <p>
      The height of a rocket above the ground is <m>h(t)</m>, measured in meters,
      at time <m>t</m> seconds after launch. It is observed that
      <m>h''(t)=-4.2</m>. Which statement correctly interprets this?
    </p>
  </statement>

    <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>At 12 seconds, the rocket's velocity is decreasing at a rate of 4.2 m/s per second.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>At 12 seconds, the rocket is falling back to the ground at a rate of 4.2 m/s.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. That is <m>h'(t)=-4.2</m>.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>The rocket's speed is constant.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. The second derivative is acceleration and not velocity or speed.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
          <p>The rocket falls 4.2 meters between 12 and 13 seconds.</p>
      </statement>
       <feedback>
        <p>No. This is not an average velocity; it is an acceleration.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
          <p>At 12 seconds, the rocket's height is concave up.</p>
      </statement>
       <feedback>
        <p>No. The graph of the rocket's height would be concave down at time <m>t</m>.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise> 

<exercise xml:id="exam1-s26-q8">
<statement>
  <p>
    The graph of a function <m>f(x)</m> defined on domain <m>[-5,\infty)</m> is shown in <xref ref="Sp26Ex1q8pic"/>.  
  </p>
  <figure xml:id="Sp26Ex1q8pic" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <caption>Graph of <m>f(x)</m>.</caption>
      <image source="images/Exam1Sp2026Continuity.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>A graph showing a function <m>f(x)</m> having domain of -5 to infinity.</description>
      </image>
</figure>
<ol marker="a.">
  <li> <p> List all values of <m>x</m> for which <m>f(x)</m> is not differentiable.</p> 
  </li>
  <li> <p> List all values of <m>x</m> for which <m>f(x)</m> is not continuous.</p> </li>
  <li> <p> List all values of <m>x</m> for which <m>f'(x)=0</m> </p> </li>
  <li> <p> Calculate <m>f'(0)</m>. </p> </li>
  <li> <p> Compare and contrast <m>\displaystyle \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} f(-3+h)</m> and <m>\displaystyle \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{f(-3+h)-f(-3)}{h}</m>.  </p> </li>
</ol>
</statement>
<answer>
  <p>
   <ol marker="a.">
    <li><m>x=-1,1</m> </li>
    <li><m>x=-1</m> </li>
    <li><m>x=-3</m> </li>
    <li><m>f'(0)=3</m> </li>
    <li> <p> <m>
        \displaystyle \lim_{h \rightarrow 0}f(-3+h) = f(-3) = 2
    </m>
    since
    <m>
        f
    </m>
    is continuous at
    <m>
        x=-3
    </m>
    . Meanwhile,
    <m>
        \displaystyle \lim_{h \rightarrow 0}\frac{f(-3+h)-f(-3)}{h}= 0
    </m>
    since that is the slope (or derivative) at
    <m>
        x=-3
    </m>
    .</p> </li>
   </ol> 
  </p>
</answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-s26-q9">
 <statement>
   <p>
      The limit
      <me>\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\sqrt[3]{8+h}-2}{h}</me>
      represents the derivative <m>f'(a)</m>, where:
    </p>
  </statement>

    <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>f(x)=\sqrt[3]{x}</m>, <m>a=8</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>f(x)=\sqrt[3]{x}</m>, <m>a=2</m></p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>f(x)=\sqrt[3]{8+x}</m>, <m>a=2</m></p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
          <p>None of these.</p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
          <p><m>f(x)=\sqrt[3]{8+x}</m>, <m>a=8</m></p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise> 

<exercise xml:id="exam1-s26-q11">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A meteorologist monitors the air pressure <m>P(t)</m> (in millibars) at a weather
      station over a short period of time. Measurements are taken every 2 hours.
    </p>

    <table xml:id="PressureDataExam1Sp26q11" >
        <title>Pressure data.</title>
    <tabular halign="center">
      <row>
        <cell><p>Time <m>t</m> (hours)</p></cell>
        <cell><p>0</p></cell>
        <cell><p>2</p></cell>
        <cell><p>4</p></cell>
        <cell><p>6</p></cell>
        <cell><p>8</p></cell>
        <cell><p>10</p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p>Pressure <m>P(t)</m> (mb)</p></cell>
        <cell><p>1018.2</p></cell>
        <cell><p>1017.5</p></cell>
        <cell><p>1015.9</p></cell>
        <cell><p>1014.8</p></cell>
        <cell><p>1014.6</p></cell>
        <cell><p>1015.0</p></cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>
  </table>

    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <p>
          Use a central difference to estimate <m>P'(6)</m>.
          Include units.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Estimate <m>P''(6)</m> using the <em>symmetric second-difference formula</em>
          <me>
            P''(t)\approx
            \frac{P(t+h)-2P(t)+P(t-h)}{h^2} \qquad (\text{for }h \text{ small}).
          </me>
          Include units and interpret whether the pressure change is
          accelerating or decelerating at <m>t=6</m> hours.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <ol marker="a.">
    <li>
   <p> We compute:
      <md>
      <mrow> P'(6) \mathstrut \amp \approx
      \frac{P(8)-P(4)}{8-4} </mrow>
      <mrow> \mathstrut \amp =
      \frac{1014.6-1015.9}{4} </mrow>
      <mrow> \mathstrut \amp =
      -0.325 \text{ mb/hour.}</mrow> 
      </md>
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p> We compute:
      <md>
      <mrow> P''(6) \mathstrut \amp \approx
        \frac{P(8)-2P(6)+P(4)}{2^2} </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = \frac{1014.6-2(1014.8)+1015.9}{2^2} </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =
      0.225 \text{ mb}/\text{hour}^2.</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      Since <m>P''(6)&gt;0</m>, the pressure is decreasing at a decreasing rate
      (the pressure trend is decelerating).
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
  </answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-s26-q12">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let the height of an object (in feet) above the ground at time <m>t</m>
      (measured in seconds) be given by
      <me>s(t)=-4t^2+5t+3.</me>
    </p>

    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <p>
          Expand and simplify
          <m>\dfrac{s(1+h)-s(1)}{h}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Using your response to part (a), evaluate
          <m>\displaystyle \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{s(1+h)-s(1)}{h}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Interpret the meaning of the value found in part (b)
          in a physical context.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Geometrically interpret the meaning of the value found in part (b).
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>

  <answer>
    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
    <p> We compute: 
      <md>
         <mrow> \frac{s(1+h)-s(1)}{h} \mathstrut \amp = \frac{-4(1+h)^{2} + 5(1+h) + 3 - (-4(1)^{2} + 5(1)+3)}{h} </mrow>
         <mrow> \amp = \frac{-8h -4h^{2} + 5h}{h} </mrow>
         <mrow> \amp = -8-4h+5 </mrow> 
         <mrow> \amp = -3-4h. </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <me>
      \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{s(1+h)-s(1)}{h}
      = \lim_{h\to 0} -3-4h = 
      -3.
      </me>
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      At time <m>t=1</m> second, the object's instantaneous velocity is
      <m>-3</m> feet per second.  If up is the positive direction, then the object is moving downward at time <m>t=1</m>.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      The value <m>-3</m> is the slope of the tangent line to the graph of
      <m>s(t)</m> at <m>(1,s(1))</m>.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
  </answer>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>
</handout>